1. To test this module, we should simulate a environment like:
ns_in                              root namespace                              ns_out
10.0.10.2/24                       10.0.10.1/24       10.0.20.1/24            10.0.20.2/24
02:00:00:00:00:44                  02:00:00:00:00:33  02:00:00:00:00:11       02:00:00:00:00:22

[veth_in_ns]   <--------------->   [veth_in_root]      [veth_out_root]   <--------------->   [veth_out_ns]
                                        ^                      |
                                        |                      |
                                        |                      |
                                   module hooks here           +---- packets re-sent here
                                   (NF_INET_PRE_ROUTING)

2. To simulate above env, do following bash cmd:
# Create two network namespaces:
# ns_in  = simulated ingress host
# ns_out = simulated egress-side host
sudo ip netns add ns_in
sudo ip netns add ns_out

# Create two veth pairs:
# 1) ingress pair:  veth_in_root  <-> veth_in_ns
# 2) egress pair:   veth_out_root <-> veth_out_ns
sudo ip link add veth_in_root type veth peer name veth_in_ns
sudo ip link add veth_out_root type veth peer name veth_out_ns

# Move one end of each veth pair into the corresponding namespace
# so each pair connects root namespace to a different netns
sudo ip link set veth_in_ns netns ns_in
sudo ip link set veth_out_ns netns ns_out

# Set MAC addresses for the egress-side veth pair
# These should match the MACs hardcoded in the kernel module:
# veth_out_root = source MAC used by the module
# veth_out_ns   = destination MAC used by the module
sudo ip link set veth_out_root address 02:00:00:00:00:11
sudo ip netns exec ns_out ip link set veth_out_ns address 02:00:00:00:00:22

# Set MAC addresses for the ingress-side veth pair
# These are mainly for clarity/debugging in packet captures
sudo ip link set veth_in_root address 02:00:00:00:00:33
sudo ip netns exec ns_in ip link set veth_in_ns address 02:00:00:00:00:44

# Assign IP addresses on the root-namespace side
# veth_in_root  = ingress-facing interface
# veth_out_root = egress-facing interface
sudo ip addr add 10.0.10.1/24 dev veth_in_root
sudo ip addr add 10.0.20.1/24 dev veth_out_root

# Assign IP addresses on the namespace side
# ns_in sends traffic toward 10.0.10.1
# ns_out receives the re-sent packets on 10.0.20.2
sudo ip netns exec ns_in ip addr add 10.0.10.2/24 dev veth_in_ns
sudo ip netns exec ns_out ip addr add 10.0.20.2/24 dev veth_out_ns

# Bring up the root-side interfaces
sudo ip link set veth_in_root up
sudo ip link set veth_out_root up

# Bring up loopback and ingress-side interface inside ns_in
sudo ip netns exec ns_in ip link set lo up
sudo ip netns exec ns_in ip link set veth_in_ns up

# Bring up loopback and egress-side interface inside ns_out
sudo ip netns exec ns_out ip link set lo up
sudo ip netns exec ns_out ip link set veth_out_ns up

3. Note that the mac addr and ip addr should not be changed, because it is hardcoded in the module src code.
